From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 4 <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-27
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: NAPI-hooked BMan refill from the XSK fill ring

M3-3 step 4 (spec sec 6.1.3, "NAPI-hooked BMan refill"). Wires the
xsk_pool fill-ring -> BMan-pool top-up loop into the per-CPU NAPI
poll's tail, immediately after xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup arming.
Pure additive change; with no XSK pool bound (default flavor) the
new flavor-op callback is a NULL deref under RCU and the rest of the
loop walks zero qbands. With a pool bound (vpp flavor + xsk_bind),
the callback measures bman_pool_get_count() and tops the BMan pool
back up from the XSK fill ring whenever depth < refill threshold.

Three coordinated changes:

  1. New ops->napi_refill callback on struct dpaa_qmgmt_ops.

     Added to dpaa_flavor.h after xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup, same
     calling convention (priv pointer only -- no per-queue context).
     The flavor module iterates priv->xsk_bpool[] internally.

  2. Call site in dpaa_eth_poll().

     Folded into the EXISTING rcu_read_lock() region that hosts the
     xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup call. No additional RCU section, no
     additional ops dereference -- the local `ops` from the prior
     rcu_dereference() is reused.

  3. New u64 xsk_bman_refill_batches counter on struct dpaa_priv,
     exposed via ethtool -S as "xsk_bman_refill_batches".

     Bumped once per non-empty xsk_buff_alloc_batch() -> bman_release()
     round-trip. The pre-existing xsk_bman_starve counter (defined by
     patch 0079, never wired before) is now bumped whenever
     bman_pool_get_count() < DPAA1_XSK_MIN_DEPTH at refill time, giving
     operators an early warning that the fill ring is draining faster
     than the kernel can top up.

Flavor-module body (af_xdp_pool_main.c):

     af_xdp_pool_napi_refill() walks priv->xsk_max_qbands. For each
     bound (priv->xsk_bpool[qband] non-NULL) qband:
       - RCU-deref priv->xsk_pool[qband] (skip if NULL)
       - Read bman_pool_get_count(bpool); skip if >= DPAA1_XSK_REFILL_THRESHOLD
       - Bump priv->xsk_bman_starve if depth < DPAA1_XSK_MIN_DEPTH
       - Compute batch size: 256 if starving, 32 otherwise
       - xsk_buff_alloc_batch() into local handles[] (stack-allocated)
       - Translate each xdp_buff DMA to bm_buffer via bm_buffer_set64()
       - bman_release() the batch
       - Bump priv->xsk_bman_refill_batches if n > 0

     The 256-entry batch ceiling matches the per-call stack budget
     (256 x sizeof(struct bm_buffer) = 8 KiB + 256 x sizeof(struct
     xdp_buff *) = 2 KiB = 10 KiB) and matches BMan's 8-buffer
     release window (bman_release() loops internally in 8-deep
     chunks). On steady state with 32-deep refills running once
     per NAPI completion, the cost is O(32) DMA accesses on a path
     that already touched O(64) DQRR slots -- negligible overhead.

Validation gates (DUT, default-flavor ISO):

  G1: priv->xsk_bman_refill_batches and priv->xsk_bman_starve both
      stay 0 across kernel-skbuf line-rate iperf3. Confirms the
      ops->napi_refill walk short-circuits on the
      priv->xsk_bpool[qband] == NULL test (no XSK pool ever bound on
      default flavor -> xsk_bpool stays NULL on all qbands -> the
      inner xsk_buff_alloc_batch / bman_release is never reached).
  G2: dmesg clean, no WARN/BUG/Oops/probe errors.
  G3: ethtool -S eth1 shows both new counter lines
      ("xsk_bman_refill_batches", and "xsk_bman_starve" which 0079
      registered but until this patch was never incremented).
  G4: iperf3 eth1->lxc200 within single-run jitter of patch 0083's
      929/928 Mbps reference. The new call adds at most one RCU read-
      section deref + one function-pointer comparison per NAPI
      completion (~ns level).
  G5 (deferred, vpp flavor): with /tmp/xsk_bind_test eth4 0 --zerocopy
      bound and iperf3 traffic flowing on band 0, xsk_bman_refill_batches
      MUST increment, and xsk_bman_starve MUST stay 0 as long as the
      kernel keeps up. Verifies steady-state refill actually drives
      BMan.

Carries forward the strict ordering of the spec sec 6.1.3 "refill
discipline": refill happens AFTER napi_complete_done() and AFTER
xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup arming, so any userspace wakeup arriving in
the interim still finds need_wakeup asserted (the matching
xsk_clear_rx_need_wakeup will land with the ZC RX hot-path in 0085).

The macro DPAA1_XSK_REFILL_THRESHOLD (256) and DPAA1_XSK_MIN_DEPTH
(64) are defined in dpaa_eth.h since patch 0071.

Files touched:

  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_flavor.h
    - add napi_refill to struct dpaa_qmgmt_ops
  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
    - add u64 xsk_bman_refill_batches
  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c
    - call ops->napi_refill(priv) from dpaa_eth_poll() tail
  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_ethtool.c
    - append "xsk_bman_refill_batches" to dpaa_stats_xsk[]
  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
    - implement af_xdp_pool_napi_refill()
    - wire .napi_refill into af_xdp_pool_qmgmt_ops

Spec reference: specs/dpaa1-afxdp-modernization-spec.md v5.0 sec 6.1.3.
Depends on: 0068..0083 (full M0+M1+M2+M3-3-step-1+2a+2b+2c+3 stack).


